        "Recognize that hydrophobicity enables passive diffusion across phospholipid membranes without active transport"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Analyze the nanobody delivery mechanism and what receptor binding accomplishes",
      "atomics": [
        "Establish that the nanobody binds a surface orphan receptor on hepatic cells, concentrating the payload at the outer leaflet of the plasma membrane",
        "Recognize that receptor binding localizes the hydrophobic payload in immediate proximity to the lipid bilayer",
        "Identify that membrane proximity allows partitioning of the hydrophobic molecule into the bilayer independent of receptor signaling"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Evaluate why endocytosis is not required and what alternative uptake route exists",
      "atomics": [
        "Confirm the PI's statement implies the drug enters cells even without receptor-mediated endocytosis",
        "Rule out clathrin-mediated endocytosis, macropinocytosis, and phagocytosis as requirements since receptor does not canonically induce them",
        "Conclude that passive transcellular diffusion through the lipid bilayer, driven by the hydrophobic nature of the payload, is the operative mechanism"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Reconcile the nanobody-receptor interaction with passive diffusion as the entry route",
      "atomics": [
        "Understand that the nanobody serves only as a targeting/localization moiety to bring the payload to the cell surface, not to trigger endocytosis",
        "Confirm that once the hydrophobic payload is membrane-proximal, it spontaneously partitions into and traverses the bilayer via passive diffusion"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "global_atomics": [
    "Verify that passive diffusion is consistent with all constraints: hydrophobic payload, no required endocytosis, orphan receptor, hepatic cell context",
    "State the answer: the PI depends on passive (membrane) diffusion for intracellular drug delivery"
  ],
  "gold_actions": {
    "global": "Determine that passive diffusion through the lipid bilayer is the cellular process enabling hydrophobic payload uptake when receptor-mediated endocytosis is absent.",
    "subtasks": [
      {
        "subtask": "Identify payload as small hydrophobic molecule enabling membrane permeation",
        "atomics": [
          "Classify payload as hydrophobic → high partition coefficient into lipid bilayer",
          "Apply Overton's rule: lipid solubility predicts passive membrane permeability",
          "Conclude hydrophobic molecules cross membranes by passive diffusion without protein assistance"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Determine that nanobody-receptor binding concentrates payload at the membrane surface",
        "atomics": [
          "Map nanobody → orphan receptor binding event to surface localization of hydrophobic payload",
          "Recognize membrane proximity creates favorable thermodynamic gradient for hydrophobic partitioning into bilayer",
          "Establish that receptor signaling is not required for this partitioning step"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Exclude endocytosis and identify passive diffusion as the actual uptake mechanism",
        "atomics": [
          "Eliminate receptor-mediated endocytosis (orphan receptor lacks canonical endocytic signaling)",
          "Eliminate phagocytosis (payload is a small molecule, not a particle; process not relevant here)",
          "Identify passive transcellular diffusion as the mechanism consistent with all stated constraints"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Confirm nanobody role is targeting not internalization signaling",
        "atomics": [
          "Assign nanobody function = cell-surface targeting/anchoring only",
          "Confirm hydrophobic molecule dissociates or diffuses from conjugate into bilayer upon membrane contact"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "global_atomics": [
      "Cross-check: hydrophobic + membrane-proximal + no endocytosis required → passive diffusion is the only consistent answer",
      "Final answer: passive (membrane) diffusion"
    ]
  }
